  "prompt": "Why astronauts have a white and an orange-coloured space suit?",
  "response": "Astronauts typically use two main types of spacesuits for different purposes:\n\n1. White Extravehicular Mobility Unit (EMU) - Used during spacewalks (EVA - Extravehicular Activity)\n- Provides protection from extreme temperatures in space\n- Reflects sunlight to prevent overheating\n- Designed for external activities outside the spacecraft\n- Provides life support and protection from radiation and micrometeorites\n\n2. Orange Advanced Crew Escape Suit (ACES) - Used during launch and re-entry\n- Also called the \"Pumpkin Suit\"\n- Provides protection during critical phases of spaceflight\n- Designed for emergency situations like spacecraft depressurization\n- Includes survival gear like communications equipment\n- Highly visible color for easier rescue if needed\n- Used primarily during Space Shuttle missions\n\nThe color and design of each spacesuit serve specific functional purposes related to the astronauts' safety and mission requirements. The white suit is for external space activities, while the orange suit is for critical flight phases and potential emergency scenarios.\n\nModern spacesuits like those used in the NASA Artemis program might have slightly different designs, but the fundamental principles remain similar.",
